    "pn1081": {
        "id": "pn1081",
        "title": "Sleepless in Social Media: Effects of Sleep Duration on Focus and Computer Usage",
        "abstract": "The amount of sleep people receive has become a pressing societal concern. While studies show that IT use affects sleep, here we examine the converse: how sleep duration might affect IT use. We conducted an in situ study, tracking 76 college students for seven days, all waking hours. We logged computer and phone use and collected sleep diaries and daily surveys. Our results show that with less sleep, students spend significantly longer durations on the computer, with shorter focus, and increased time on social media sites. The relationship of sleep duration with social media use is mediated by computer time and focus duration. Less sleep is also associated with higher perceived productivity and work pressure. Our results have theoretical implications for multitasking: physiological and cognitive reasons could explain more social media use and computer activity switches, due to less sleep. We present design ideas for detecting and improving sleep behaviors.",
        "authors": [
            {
                "name": "Gloria Mark",
                "email": "gmark@uci.edu",
                "dept": "",
                "institution": "University of California, Irvine",
                "city": "Irvine",
                "country": "United States",
                "location": "Irvine, United States",
                "affiliation": "University of California, Irvine"
